  "target_response": {
    "text": "That's a much bigger conclusion than seven days of tags can carry. What your log actually shows: on 7 tagged skipped-lunch days versus 41 comparison days, next-day recovery averaged about 4.8 points lower — an association graded low confidence, and 7 tagged days is a thin sample by any standard. It's also tangled: your skipped lunches happen on your busiest days, so the data can't distinguish the missing meal from the stress, the extra hours, or the later night that come with it. A plausible mechanism exists — training or long days while underfueled can show up in next-morning numbers — but plausible isn't proven. The practical experiment: keep something quick on hand for busy days for a few weeks and watch whether the pattern fades. And if skipping ever stops being about busyness and starts being about restriction, that's a conversation for a professional, not a chart.",
